title: For Sale:  AR 15-5.56/.223 -Not Cheap, 1 of a Kind
postcontent: This isn't an inexpensive rifle-there are plenty on the market now, so if money is your primary concern, don't look any further. Why is this one of a kind? It was not built to sell or for a showpiece.People often refer to their gun as "rare" to get your attention or justify a high price. This rifle starts with a Palmetto receiver sn SC000XXX. If you're familiar with Palmetto you recognize that's not a normal SN. The SC denoted South Carolina and the manufacturer of the receiver-FN.This is one of 500 made by FN for Palmetto while FN was only building for the military, and prior to them entering the commercial market.The barrel is a Black Hole Weaponry 16 inch 1-8 twist polygonal barrel, mid length, stainless steel, pencil configuration. Polygonal barrels are noted as the most accurate, durable, and easily cleaned type. Additionally the rifle uses an M16 stainless steel hd bolt carrier group,Midwest Industries 15 inch free float FDE SS series Gen2 handguard, Ergo F93 8 position FDE stock and buffer tube assy.,ALG fire control group, Vltor BCM charging handle and is topped with a Nikon P223 BDC scope and mount.Included are 14 magazines (Magpul and Thermold) 20 & 30 round capacity, and approximately 700 rounds factory .223 ammo.This is the last of 3 rifles built and has been test fired, but not sighted in.The other 2 rifles were extremely accurate out to 300 yards and capable of placing 40 rounds (2-20 rd mags) into a 2 inch diameter hole at 35 yards using a Vortex strikefire red dot sight.Not looking for trades-emptying safe, only reason this is for sale.Must pick up in Moody, AL drivers license or pistol permit, and sign bill of sale. Serious Inquiries only.

postcontent: This is a Polish Tantal, a variant of the AK-74, caliber 5.45X39 (NOT an AK-47).  I have a dated reciept showing I paid $600 (not incl tax) for this new in 2008 after it was built by Elk River Tool & Die when they were located in Houston and doing their best work.  I never liked the wire folding paratrooper stock that came on it: it was impossible to shoulder/cheek weld it was so short.  I installed a Magpul MOE stock and grip and the rifle is SO much easier/fun to shoot now.  I installed a Midwest Industries short picatinny rail mount that locks up like a ROCK where the rear sight was: it is hands down the best way to mount a red dot on these rifles.  Absolutely solid and you can completely disassemble the rifle without removing the mount or the optic, and of course the rear sight can be easily re-installed if you want to go back to stock iron sights.  The Primary Arms red dot is zeroed in at 100m and can put every shot in a 3" group, and they are all round holes...no "keyholing", as I hear some Tantals did that were built by other builders.  I have another $150 in the stock,grip,mount, and red dot.  So for $750 (what I have in it), you will have one of the best looking/shooting AK-74 variants anywhere.  I will include 2 East German bakelite 30 round mags for this price; these sell for $45 & up when you can find them.  I have a total of 21 mags (all 30 round, 4 are East German bakelites, the rest are polymer steel-reinforced Bulgarian) and 3 CASES of Russian 7N6 military steel penetrator ammo, each case with 2 (two) 1,080 round sealed steel "spam cans" (thats 6,480 rounds), and another 1,000+ rounds of Wolf non-corrosive ammo, all of which has been properly stored.  Buy the rifle and I will sell you as many mags and ammo as you want, at a fair price.  Note: I have recently function tested ALL the mags;
